## The Total Ring Number

Most buyers budget for a stone. Then they see the setting price and treat it as a surprise extra. That is the wrong way to plan this purchase.

The Total Ring Number is simple: stone price plus setting price equals the ring you actually take home. It is one number. Plan it as one number from the start.

For an emerald cut specifically, the stone should get 70–80% of your total budget. Here is why. The emerald cut's hall-of-mirrors appeal lives in the stone. The step-cut facets, the VS1 clarity, the length-to-width ratio — all of that is in the stone. A $5,000 total ring budget should put $3,500–$4,000 on the stone and $1,000–$1,500 on the setting. Flip that ratio and you end up with an over-designed setting on an under-quality stone that looks foggy and dull.

